<p>
  When physicists say
  "kinetic energy" and "potential energy,"
  they don't actually mean two specific types of energy
  but actually two <strong>broad categories</strong>.
  In fact, <em>every</em> type of energy
  can be categorized as either
  a <strong>kinetic energy</strong>
  or a <strong>potential energy</strong>.
</p>

<p class = 'definition' data-word = 'Kinetic Energy'>
  All types of energy
  held by something in motion
  are <strong>kinetic energy</strong>.
</p>
<p class = 'definition' data-word = 'Potential Energy'>
  All types of energy
  held by something that is not
  moving, but has the <em>potential</em>
  to begin moving are <strong>potential energy</strong>.
</p>


