<h4>
  Translational Kinetic Energy vs. Thermal Energy
</h4>

<p>
  Everything is made of atoms and molecules,
  and when those atoms and molecules
  move, it has kinetic energy!
  However, atoms and molecules can move in two different ways,
  and those two different ways indicate two different types of kinetic energy:
  translational kinetic energy and thermal energy.
</p>

<p class = 'definition' data-word = 'Translational Kinetic Energy'>
  Imagine a block made of molecules.
  If all of those molecules are moving in the <em>same direction</em>,
  that block has <strong>translational kinetic energy</strong>.
</p>

<p class = 'definition' data-word = 'Thermal Energy'>
  Imagine a block made of molecules.
  The molecules are <em>always</em> moving randomly!
  Because of this random motion, the molecules have
  <strong>thermal energy</strong>.
  <br>
  Objects that are cold <em>still</em> have thermal energy, just less.
</p>

